tony brooker from wikipedia free encyclopedia jump navigation search tony brooker born age 90–91 england nationality british fields computer science institutions university cambridge manchester university essex university alma mater imperial college london known for mark autocode compiler-compiler ralph anthony tony brooker born england british academic who was computer scientist known for developing mark autocode he was educated at emanuel school graduated mathematics from imperial college returned there assistant lecturer his first computer project was construction fast multiplier unit from electro-mechanical relays this was taken over by sid michaelson k d tocher incorporated into icce imperial college computing engine based on same technology by then tony had moved university cambridge computer laboratory work for maurice wilkes on software development for edsac october tony joined computing machine laboratory at manchester university where he took over from alan turing task writing programming manuals running user service on ferranti mark computer was his experience with rather tedious manchester machine-coding conventions that led him devise what was probably world's first publicly available high-level language this was mark autocode available from march therefore about two years ahead first fortran compiler throughout 1950s tony led group at manchester working on theoretical underpinnings compilers this culminated compiler-compiler seminal idea first presented at british computer society conference july by brooker morris this was subsequently implemented on ferranti atlas used for high-level language development atlas was regarded world's most powerful computer when was brought into service december mid-1960s tony helped inaugurate uk's first computer science degree course at manchester he moved essex university take up university's founding chair computer science first essex computer science graduates obtained their degrees summer he retired further reading 